  "text": "The women believed that mental illness can be treated with counseling (individual or group), yet, mainly because of side effects, they expressed ambivalence toward medication use. Their concern is supported by a recent study in which it was found that African Americans were more likely to be prescribed older, less tolerable, and less safe tricyclic antidepressants than Whites, who were significantly more likely to receive newer, safer, and more tolerable serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) for depression [CITATION_1] . Whether because of fear of side effects, insurance status, or mistrust in the health care organization, African Americans are less likely to fill prescriptions for antidepressant medications. A study by [CITATION_2] found that only 29% of African Americans fill a prescription, compared to 51% of Whites.",
